Defendant Angie Lee Medrano in court with attorney Parker C. Mathers.  Defendant Angie Lee Medrano in custody.  Jesica Ann Ballenger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Sworn: Spanish Interpreter Dawn Maldonado (present for victim).  Negotiations set forth by the state.

AS TO COUNT 1:  The defendant was advised of her constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  

AS TO COUNT 2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on state's motion, the Court orders Count 2 DISMISSED AND READ-IN for the purpose of today's hearing.

Sentencing proceeded.   Statements made by Teresa F.-G., State, defense, and defendant. 
 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 6 1/2 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 127  days served.  The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS, 6 MONTHS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 4 YEARS.  The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program AFTER SERVING THE FIRST 18 MONTH OF THIS SENTENCE.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Obtain Mental health assessment and successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Take any prescribed medication only in the manner/dosage as prescribed by a treating physician;
*Obtain AODA assessment and successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Participate with random urine screens;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*Cognitive thinking program;
*Participate in vocational training if available;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school and part time employment;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay all mandatory applicable surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs after restitution paid in full; 

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court ordered restitution in the stipulated amount of $940.00 to Teresa F.-G.  and $8,059.69 to Crime Victim Compensation Fund (claim #141888-16).  The Court ordered that all financial obligations and restitution be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment. Restitution to be paid first.  Appeal rights given by Court.
